<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=316&amp;p=19317#p19317"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">GauravK wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />The screenshot is from Classic Shell's Start Menu with the Classic skin running on Windows 7 with the Classic theme and Quick Launch enabled.<br /></div>I did some search and found out a pair of videos on utube like this <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e77JpO8Uk8M" class="postlink">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e77JpO8Uk8M</a> or this <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y1q_nlcCjyA" class="postlink">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y1q_nlcCjyA</a>.<br />To cut the long story short, MS doesn't throw away anything including &quot;classic theme&quot; from W2K.<br />Putting the Classic theme back in service in W8 involves: manipulations with dwm.exe, ribbon removal, making windows 7 shellstyle.dll mod on shellstyle.dll in system32, deleting Windows.UI.Immersive.dll, installing classic shell start menu, installing the old task manager, exporting HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Control Panel\Appearance\Schemes from windows XP/2003, importing into windows 8.<br />Pressing Ctrl-Alt-Del brings black screen with no way out of it.<br /><br />In the first video the guy just fools around with stopping the dwm.exe - just a proof of concept.<br />The second one in the comments contains a complete guide for making classic theme in W8.1.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10180">JonJon</a> — Fri May 08, 2015 10:19 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
